#Text=Giulio Fiesco
#Text=Giulio Fiesco ( possibly born ? 1519 , fl. 1550 – 1570 ) was an Italian composer of the Renaissance , active in Ferrara , known for his madrigals .

#Text=He was the first composer to set the poetry of Giovanni Battista Guarini , the most often-set poet by madrigalists of the late 16th century , and was an important court composer for the rich musical establishment of the Este family in Ferrara .
#Text=Life
#Text=Details of Fiesco 's life are sketchy .
#Text=He was probably born in Ferrara and seems to have spent most of his life there .

#Text=François-Joseph Fétis , the 19th-century French musicologist , claimed dates of 1519 to 1586 for Fiesco , but as he did not give his sources , it is not known if he had access to some documentation no longer extant .
#Text=Alfred Einstein also reports these dates in The Italian Madrigal , with the additional detail that Fiesco was likely a lutenist . [ 1 ]
#Text=Fiesco was connected to the Estense court as indicated by the dedications in his madrigal collections , and may have been employed at the church of San Francesco , since he is buried there .
#Text=It is also possible that he was employed personally by Cardinal Ippolito II d'Este . [ 2 ]
#Text=In 1567 the poet Giovanni Battista Guarini entered into the service of Alfonso II d'Este , Duke of Ferrara .

#Text=No poet was more influential on music history in the late Renaissance than Guarini , whose works were set more often by madrigal composers than those of any other poet ; Fiesco was significant as the first composer ever to set Guarini 's poetry to music .
#Text=Not only did he set poetry by Guarini , but in the dedication to the madrigal book
#Text=he claimed he wrote it at the poet 's request : and he dedicated the entire group of compositions to Lucrezia and Leonora d'Este . [ 2 ]
#Text=Fiesco is not mentioned in any known payment records from Ferrara , a useful source of information on musicians , and he vanishes completely from written record around 1570 .
#Text=The publication dates of his madrigal collections range from 1554 to 1569 . [ 2 ]
#Text=Works and influence
#Text=All of Fiesco 's surviving works are secular and vocal .
#Text=He published four books of madrigals , in 1554 , 1563 , 1567 , and 1569 , dedicating all four to members of the Este family .
#Text=Of these four books , the first and last have gotten the most attention .

#Text=His compositions in the first book of 1554 show most directly the influence of Cipriano de Rore , the most renowned mid-century composer of madrigals , who was then the maestro di cappella in Ferrara for Duke Ercole II d'Este .

#Text=Fiesco 's compositions in this book are for four voices , and include madrigals in the classic style , chromatically experimental works ( for example Bacio soave , which shows also the influence of Nicola Vicentino , who actively encouraged such experiments ) , as well as music likely intended for performance at dramatic events staged for the Este family .
#Text=Poetry he sets includes works by Boccaccio , Giovanni Batista Strozzi , Bernardo Tasso , Sannazaro , Ludovico Ariosto , and Petrarch . [ 3 ]
#Text=Fiesco 's last book of madrigals , the Musica nuova , for five voices , is his most famous , for it is the first appearance of the poetry of Guarini set to music .
#Text=Fourteen out of the fifteen poems in the collection are sonnets , and the style matches the elegance of the language , attaining considerable virtuosity in text setting . [ 4 ]

#Text=Some of the settings are innovative harmonically and rhythmically , with one madrigal , S'armi pur d'ira disdegnoso ed empio , foreshadowing the Baroque stile concitato of rapid declamation over a homophonic texture . [ 5 ]
#Text=Not all of Fiesco 's works are madrigals .
#Text=He published a few secular songs in lighter current forms such as the greghesca and the napolitane , forms of Venetian and Neapolitan origin respectively . [ 2 ]
